review TCL call number: SF Shannon S Stephanie’s rating: 3.5 stars This is an intricate and deviously detailed story. More so the variety of characters and tit TCL call number: SF Shannon S Stephanie’s rating: 3.5 stars This is an intricate and deviously detailed story. More so the variety of characters and titles these certain individuals posses such as pyromancer, necromancer, cartomancer, or a summoner. And what exactly do they mean? HA! Well my friends, welcome to the world of clairvoyance, and if you so happen to be one you will not be regarded as weird or crazy, but lethal! The year is somewhere in the vicinity of 2059 and the location is London, England. Paige Mahoney is a clairvoyant; an extremely rare one. And what exactly happens to people that posses such rare gifts? Well of course they’re hunted down! When the day finally comes she is taken to a nearby “abandoned” city, and learns of the Rephaim, a savage group of non-humans who pretend to take-in clairvoyants and rehabilitate them, but in actuality they’re consuming them and in some cases, stealing their gifts. Overall, it’s a good read. The one downside, and of course this is all personal, was the lack of suspense. For a story like this, you know running-from the law and trying to escape the “netherworld”, I was expecting more challenges, but there weren’t that many and sometimes the story fell flat. Don’t let my points of view dissuade you. “Bone Season” is a series, and the next book could potentially be better. ...more

review TCL Call#: MYSTERY Winspear Madeleine - 3 stars Recommended to me as a book for someone who liked Downton Abbey, I have to say I'm not disappointed on t TCL Call#: MYSTERY Winspear Madeleine - 3 stars Recommended to me as a book for someone who liked Downton Abbey, I have to say I'm not disappointed on that count. It's very Upstairs/Downstairs with the maid who rises above her station - kind of like the first season on Downton. This book loses it for me a bit in a contrived writing style. The author starts off fully staging a mystery and then just full stops and begins a historical section, not as flashbacks, but fully stops the narrative. We're taken backwards in character time and spend several chapters living there; then just as suddenly we're transported right back into the mystery which then chugs along only to end up trying to marry the two narratives. I'm not saying it can't be done; it's just not well done here. Looking forward to book #2 in the hopes that now that the back story is out the author will no longer feel the need to tell two stories on independent tracks. ...more
